lessons.explanation:
In programming, a variable is a container that holds data. Think of it like a labeled box where you can store a value and retrieve it later. In Java, every variable must be declared with a specific data type before it can be used. This is what makes Java a statically typed language.

Declaring a Variable
The syntax for declaring a variable in Java is: dataType variableName = value;
For example: int age = 25;
Here, 'int' is the data type, 'age' is the variable name, and 25 is the initial value.

Primitive Data Types
Java has 8 primitive data types. These are the most basic types built directly into the language:

1. byte: Stores whole numbers from -128 to 127. Uses 1 byte of memory. Example: byte b = 100;
2. short: Stores whole numbers from -32,768 to 32,767. Uses 2 bytes. Example: short s = 5000;
3. int: Stores whole numbers from about -2 billion to 2 billion. Uses 4 bytes. This is the most commonly used integer type. Example: int count = 42;
4. long: Stores very large whole numbers. Uses 8 bytes. Add 'L' suffix to literals. Example: long bigNumber = 9999999999L;
5. float: Stores decimal numbers with about 6-7 decimal digits of precision. Uses 4 bytes. Add 'f' suffix. Example: float price = 9.99f;
6. double: Stores decimal numbers with about 15 decimal digits of precision. Uses 8 bytes. This is the default for decimals. Example: double pi = 3.14159265358979;
7. boolean: Stores true or false. Uses 1 bit effectively. Example: boolean isJavaFun = true;
8. char: Stores a single character (letter, digit, symbol). Uses 2 bytes. Use single quotes. Example: char grade = 'A';

Reference Types
Beyond primitives, Java has reference types. The most important beginner reference type is String. A String stores a sequence of characters (text). Example: String name = "Alice";
Strings use double quotes. We will cover Strings in depth in Lesson 9.

Naming Conventions
Java variable names should follow camelCase: start with a lowercase letter, and capitalize the first letter of each subsequent word. Examples: firstName, totalAmount, isUserLoggedIn.
Variable names cannot start with a number, cannot contain spaces, and cannot be Java reserved words (like int, class, public).

Constants
If you want a variable whose value should never change, use the 'final' keyword: final double TAX_RATE = 0.08;
Constants are typically named in ALL_CAPS_WITH_UNDERSCORES.

Type Casting
Sometimes you need to convert between types. Widening casting (smaller to larger) is automatic: int x = 5; double y = x; (works fine). Narrowing casting (larger to smaller) requires explicit cast: double d = 9.7; int i = (int) d; (i becomes 9, decimal part is lost).

examples.code:
public class DataTypes {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        byte age = 25;
        short year = 2024;
        int population = 1000000;
        long distanceToSun = 149600000L;
        float temperature = 36.6f;
        double pi = 3.14159265358979;
        boolean isJavaFun = true;
        char initial = 'J';

        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
        System.out.println("Year: " + year);
        System.out.println("Population: " + population);
        System.out.println("Distance to Sun: " + distanceToSun);
        System.out.println("Temperature: " + temperature);
        System.out.println("Pi: " + pi);
        System.out.println("Is Java fun? " + isJavaFun);
        System.out.println("Initial: " + initial);
    }
}

public class TypeCasting {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Widening: int to double (automatic)
        int intValue = 42;
        double doubleValue = intValue;
        System.out.println("Widened: " + doubleValue); // 42.0

        // Narrowing: double to int (explicit cast)
        double price = 19.99;
        int roundedPrice = (int) price;
        System.out.println("Narrowed: " + roundedPrice); // 19 (decimal lost)

        // Constant
        final double TAX_RATE = 0.08;
        System.out.println("Tax rate: " + TAX_RATE);
    }
}

public class Arithmetic {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 17;
        int b = 5;

        System.out.println("a + b = " + (a + b));  // 22
        System.out.println("a - b = " + (a - b));  // 12
        System.out.println("a * b = " + (a * b));  // 85
        System.out.println("a / b = " + (a / b));  // 3 (integer division)
        System.out.println("a % b = " + (a % b));  // 2 (remainder)

        // Float division
        double result = (double) a / b;
        System.out.println("Float division: " + result); // 3.4
    }
}

public class LogicDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int age = 20;
        boolean hasID = true;

        // Comparison
        System.out.println("Is adult: " + (age >= 18));         // true
        System.out.println("Is not 30: " + (age != 30));        // true

        // Logical
        boolean canEnter = (age >= 18) && hasID;
        System.out.println("Can enter: " + canEnter);           // true

        boolean needsCheck = (age < 18) || !hasID;
        System.out.println("Needs check: " + needsCheck);       // false
    }
}

lessons.explanation:
Programs need to make decisions. Should we show a welcome message? Is the user old enough to access this content? Did the user enter the correct password? Conditional statements allow your program to execute different blocks of code depending on whether certain conditions are true or false.

The if Statement
The simplest conditional is the if statement. It executes a block of code only if its condition is true:
if (condition) {
    // code runs if condition is true
}

The if-else Statement
Use if-else when you want to execute one block of code if the condition is true and a different block if it is false:
if (condition) {
    // runs if true
} else {
    // runs if false
}

The if-else if-else Chain
When you have multiple conditions to check, chain them:
if (condition1) {
    // runs if condition1 is true
} else if (condition2) {
    // runs if condition1 is false AND condition2 is true
} else if (condition3) {
    // runs if conditions 1 and 2 are false AND condition3 is true
} else {
    // runs if all conditions are false
}
Java checks each condition in order and executes the first one that is true. Once a match is found, it skips the rest.

Nested if Statements
You can place if statements inside other if statements. This is called nesting. Use it when you need to check secondary conditions after a primary condition is met:
if (isLoggedIn) {
    if (isAdmin) {
        System.out.println("Welcome, Admin!");
    } else {
        System.out.println("Welcome, User!");
    }
}

The switch Statement
When you need to compare a single variable against many possible values, switch is cleaner than a long if-else chain:
switch (variable) {
    case value1:
        // code
        break;
    case value2:
        // code
        break;
    default:
        // runs if no case matches
}
The break keyword is crucial — without it, execution 'falls through' to the next case. The default case is optional but recommended.

The Ternary Operator
For simple if-else assignments, Java has a shorthand called the ternary operator:
result = (condition) ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse;
Example: String status = (age >= 18) ? "adult" : "minor";
This is concise but use it only for simple cases — complex ternary operators reduce readability.

examples.code:
public class GradeCalc {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int score = 78;

        if (score >= 90) {
            System.out.println("Grade: A");
        } else if (score >= 80) {
            System.out.println("Grade: B");
        } else if (score >= 70) {
            System.out.println("Grade: C");
        } else if (score >= 60) {
            System.out.println("Grade: D");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Grade: F");
        }
    }
}

public class DayName {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int day = 3;
        String dayName;

        switch (day) {
            case 1:
                dayName = "Monday";
                break;
            case 2:
                dayName = "Tuesday";
                break;
            case 3:
                dayName = "Wednesday";
                break;
            case 4:
                dayName = "Thursday";
                break;
            case 5:
                dayName = "Friday";
                break;
            default:
                dayName = "Weekend";
        }

        System.out.println("Day: " + dayName); // Wednesday
    }
}

lessons.explanation:
Loops allow your program to execute a block of code repeatedly. Instead of writing the same code 100 times, you write it once and let a loop run it 100 times. Java has three main loop types: for, while, and do-while.

The for Loop
The for loop is ideal when you know in advance how many times you want to loop. Its structure is:
for (initialization; condition; update) {
    // loop body
}
- Initialization: runs once before the loop starts (e.g., int i = 0)
- Condition: checked before each iteration; loop continues while true
- Update: runs after each iteration (e.g., i++)

Example: for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) { System.out.println(i); }
This prints 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.

The while Loop
The while loop is ideal when you do not know in advance how many times you need to loop. It checks the condition before each iteration:
while (condition) {
    // loop body
}
If the condition is false from the start, the loop body never executes.

The do-while Loop
The do-while loop is like while, but it always runs the loop body at least once because the condition is checked after the body:
do {
    // loop body
} while (condition);
This is useful when you want to run some code at least once regardless of the condition (e.g., displaying a menu).

Nested Loops
You can put a loop inside another loop. The inner loop completes all its iterations for each iteration of the outer loop. This is useful for working with 2D data or printing patterns.

Break and Continue
break: immediately exits the loop regardless of the condition
continue: skips the rest of the current iteration and moves to the next one

For-each Loop (Enhanced for)
Java also has an enhanced for loop for iterating over arrays and collections:
for (dataType element : array) {
    // use element
}
We will use this more in the Arrays lesson.

Common Loop Pitfalls
1. Infinite loops: if the condition never becomes false (e.g., you forget i++), the loop runs forever. Always ensure the loop condition will eventually become false.
2. Off-by-one errors: starting at 0 vs 1, using < vs <=. Be precise about your loop bounds.
3. Modifying loop variable inside body: avoid changing i inside the for loop body as it leads to confusing behavior.

examples.code:
public class LoopDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // for loop: print 1 to 5
        System.out.println("For loop:");
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();

        // while loop: countdown
        System.out.println("While countdown:");
        int count = 5;
        while (count > 0) {
            System.out.print(count + " ");
            count--;
        }
        System.out.println();

        // do-while: runs at least once
        System.out.println("Do-while:");
        int x = 0;
        do {
            System.out.println("x = " + x);
            x++;
        } while (x < 3);
    }
}

public class MultiTable {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= 5; j++) {
                System.out.printf("%4d", i * j);
            }
            System.out.println();
        }
    }
}

lessons.explanation:
A method is a reusable block of code that performs a specific task. Instead of repeating the same code in multiple places, you write it once as a method and call it whenever you need it. Methods are the primary tool for organizing and reusing code in Java.

Defining a Method
A method definition has this structure:
accessModifier returnType methodName(parameters) {
    // method body
    return value; // if returnType is not void
}

Example:
public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

Breaking this down:
- public: the method is accessible from anywhere
- static: the method belongs to the class, not an instance (we will explain more in OOP lessons)
- int: the return type (this method returns an integer)
- add: the method name
- (int a, int b): parameters — values the method receives when called
- return a + b: the value returned to the caller

Calling a Method
To use a method, you call it by name and pass the required arguments:
int result = add(5, 3); // result = 8

void Methods
If a method does not return a value, its return type is 'void'. void methods perform an action but do not produce a result to use:
public static void greet(String name) {
    System.out.println("Hello, " + name + "!");
}
greet("Alice"); // Prints: Hello, Alice!

Method Parameters and Arguments
Parameters are variables listed in the method definition. Arguments are the actual values passed when calling the method. Java passes primitives by value (a copy), so changes inside the method do not affect the original variable.

Method Overloading
Java allows multiple methods with the same name as long as they have different parameter lists (different number or types of parameters). This is called overloading:
public static int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
public static double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; }
public static int add(int a, int b, int c) { return a + b + c; }
Java picks the correct version based on the argument types and count.

Variable Scope
Variables declared inside a method are local variables — they only exist within that method and cannot be accessed from outside. This is called scope. Parameters are also local to the method.

Recursion (Introduction)
A method can call itself — this is called recursion. It needs a base case (a condition to stop) and a recursive case (the call to itself with a simpler input). Classic example: factorial. factorial(5) = 5 * factorial(4) = 5 * 4 * 3 * 2 * 1 = 120.

examples.code:
public class MethodDemo {

    public static int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public static double circleArea(double radius) {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }

    public static void printSeparator() {
        System.out.println("-------------------");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Sum: " + add(10, 25));
        printSeparator();
        System.out.printf("Area: %.2f%n", circleArea(5.0));
        printSeparator();
        System.out.println("Sum again: " + add(100, 200));
    }
}

public class Factorial {

    public static long factorial(int n) {
        if (n <= 1) {
            return 1; // base case
        }
        return n * factorial(n - 1); // recursive case
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (int i = 0; i <= 10; i++) {
            System.out.println(i + "! = " + factorial(i));
        }
    }
}

import java.util.Arrays;

public class ArrayDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] numbers = {64, 25, 12, 90, 43};

        // Print original
        System.out.println("Original: " + Arrays.toString(numbers));

        // Find max
        int max = numbers[0];
        for (int n : numbers) {
            if (n > max) max = n;
        }
        System.out.println("Max: " + max);

        // Calculate average
        int sum = 0;
        for (int n : numbers) {
            sum += n;
        }
        double avg = (double) sum / numbers.length;
        System.out.printf("Average: %.2f%n", avg);

        // Sort
        Arrays.sort(numbers);
        System.out.println("Sorted: " + Arrays.toString(numbers));
    }
}

public class Grid {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[][] matrix = {
            {1, 2, 3},
            {4, 5, 6},
            {7, 8, 9}
        };

        System.out.println("Matrix:");
        for (int row = 0; row < matrix.length; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < matrix[row].length; col++) {
                System.out.printf("%3d", matrix[row][col]);
            }
            System.out.println();
        }
    }
}

public class StringDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String sentence = "  Hello, Java World!  ";

        System.out.println("Original: '" + sentence + "'");
        System.out.println("Trimmed: '" + sentence.trim() + "'");
        System.out.println("Length: " + sentence.trim().length());
        System.out.println("Uppercase: " + sentence.trim().toUpperCase());
        System.out.println("Index of 'Java': " + sentence.indexOf("Java"));
        System.out.println("Substring: " + sentence.trim().substring(7, 11));
        System.out.println("Replace: " + sentence.trim().replace("World", "Universe"));
        System.out.println("Contains 'Java': " + sentence.contains("Java"));

        String[] words = sentence.trim().split(", ");
        for (String word : words) {
            System.out.println("Word: " + word);
        }
    }
}

public class StringBuilderDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Inefficient in loops (creates many objects)
        String result = "";
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            result += "Item" + i + " ";
        }
        System.out.println(result);

        // Efficient with StringBuilder
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            sb.append("Item").append(i).append(" ");
        }
        System.out.println(sb.toString());
    }
}

