lessons.explanation:
Now that you understand OOP concepts, it is time to write actual classes and create objects. This lesson covers how to define a class with fields and methods, how to create objects using the 'new' keyword, how to access fields and methods on objects, and how to use access modifiers and getters/setters.

Defining a Class
A class is defined using the class keyword:
public class ClassName {
    // fields (instance variables)
    // methods
}
By convention, class names use PascalCase (first letter of each word capitalized): BankAccount, StudentRecord.

Fields (Instance Variables)
Fields are variables declared inside a class but outside any method. Each object gets its own copy:
public class Person {
    String name;
    int age;
    double height;
}

Creating Objects
Use the 'new' keyword followed by the class name and parentheses:
Person p1 = new Person();
Person p2 = new Person();
p1 and p2 are separate objects with their own independent data.

Accessing Fields and Methods
Use dot notation to access fields and call methods on objects:
p1.name = "Alice";
p1.age = 30;
System.out.println(p1.name);

Access Modifiers
Java access modifiers control visibility:
- public: accessible from anywhere
- private: accessible only within the class
- protected: accessible within the class and subclasses
- (default/package-private): accessible within the same package

Encapsulation with Getters and Setters
Best practice is to make fields private and provide public getter/setter methods:
private String name; // hidden
public String getName() { return name; } // getter
public void setName(String name) { this.name = name; } // setter
This allows you to add validation in setters (e.g., reject negative age values) without changing the external interface.

The 'this' Keyword
Inside a method or constructor, 'this' refers to the current object. It is used to distinguish between instance fields and local variables with the same name:
public void setAge(int age) {
    this.age = age; // this.age is the field, age is the parameter
}

Static vs Instance Members
Instance fields/methods belong to each individual object. Static fields/methods belong to the class itself and are shared across all instances. Access static members via the class name: Math.PI, Math.sqrt().

examples.code:
public class BankAccount {
    private String owner;
    private double balance;

    public String getOwner() {
        return owner;
    }

    public void setOwner(String owner) {
        this.owner = owner;
    }

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;
            System.out.println("Deposited: " + amount);
        }
    }

    public void withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0 && amount <= balance) {
            balance -= amount;
            System.out.println("Withdrew: " + amount);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Insufficient funds or invalid amount.");
        }
    }

    public void printStatement() {
        System.out.println("Account: " + owner + " | Balance: $" + balance);
    }
}

// Usage in another class:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount alice = new BankAccount();
        alice.setOwner("Alice");
        alice.deposit(1000);
        alice.withdraw(250);
        alice.printStatement();

        BankAccount bob = new BankAccount();
        bob.setOwner("Bob");
        bob.deposit(500);
        bob.printStatement();
    }
}

lessons.explanation:
A constructor is a special method used to initialize a new object. When you use 'new ClassName()', Java calls the constructor to set up the object's initial state. Understanding constructors is essential for creating well-initialized objects.

What Makes a Constructor Special?
1. A constructor has the same name as the class
2. A constructor has no return type (not even void)
3. A constructor is called automatically when an object is created with 'new'

The Default Constructor
If you do not write any constructor, Java provides a default no-argument constructor that does nothing — fields are initialized to their default values (0 for numbers, null for objects, false for booleans).
Once you define any constructor yourself, Java no longer provides the default one.

Parameterized Constructors
A constructor can take parameters to initialize fields right when the object is created:
public class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    public Person(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }
}
Person alice = new Person("Alice", 30); // immediately initialized

Constructor Overloading
Just like methods, constructors can be overloaded. You can have multiple constructors with different parameter lists:
public Person() { // no-arg constructor
    this.name = "Unknown";
    this.age = 0;
}
public Person(String name) { // one-arg constructor
    this.name = name;
    this.age = 0;
}
public Person(String name, int age) { // two-arg constructor
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
}

Using this() to Call Another Constructor
Inside a constructor, you can call another constructor in the same class using this():
public Person(String name) {
    this(name, 0); // calls Person(String, int)
}
The this() call must be the first statement in the constructor.

Copy Constructor
A copy constructor creates a new object as a copy of another:
public Person(Person other) {
    this.name = other.name;
    this.age = other.age;
}
Person copy = new Person(original);

Constructors vs Methods
Constructors initialize objects; they are not regular methods. They cannot be called after object creation (except through this() or super()). Every class must have at least one constructor (either default or explicit).

examples.code:
public class Student {
    private String name;
    private int grade;
    private double gpa;

    // No-arg constructor with defaults
    public Student() {
        this("Unknown", 9, 0.0);
    }

    // Name only
    public Student(String name) {
        this(name, 9, 0.0);
    }

    // Full constructor
    public Student(String name, int grade, double gpa) {
        this.name = name;
        this.grade = grade;
        this.gpa = gpa;
    }

    public void describe() {
        System.out.printf("Student: %s | Grade: %d | GPA: %.2f%n",
            name, grade, gpa);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student();
        Student s2 = new Student("Alice");
        Student s3 = new Student("Bob", 11, 3.85);

        s1.describe();
        s2.describe();
        s3.describe();
    }
}

public class Animal {
    protected String name;
    protected int age;

    public Animal(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    public void eat() {
        System.out.println(name + " is eating.");
    }

    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println(name + " makes a sound.");
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return name + " (age " + age + ")";
    }
}

public class Dog extends Animal {
    private String breed;

    public Dog(String name, int age, String breed) {
        super(name, age); // calls Animal constructor
        this.breed = breed;
    }

    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println(name + " says: Woof!");
    }

    public void fetch() {
        System.out.println(name + " fetches the ball!");
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return super.toString() + " [" + breed + "]"; 
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog rex = new Dog("Rex", 3, "Labrador");
        rex.eat();          // inherited from Animal
        rex.makeSound();    // overridden in Dog
        rex.fetch();        // Dog-specific
        System.out.println(rex); // uses toString()
    }
}

lessons.explanation:
Polymorphism means 'many forms'. In Java, polymorphism allows objects of different classes to be treated through a common interface or superclass reference. A single method call can behave differently depending on the actual object type. This is one of OOP's most powerful and practical features.

Compile-Time Polymorphism (Method Overloading)
We already saw this in the methods lesson: multiple methods with the same name but different parameters. The compiler picks the right version based on argument types. This is resolved at compile time.

Runtime Polymorphism (Method Overriding)
This is the more powerful form. When a superclass reference holds a subclass object, and a method is called, Java calls the subclass's overridden version at runtime:
Animal a = new Dog("Rex", 3, "Lab"); // Animal reference, Dog object
a.makeSound(); // calls Dog's makeSound(), not Animal's!
This is dynamic dispatch. Java decides which method to call based on the actual object type, not the reference type.

Polymorphism with Arrays and Parameters
Polymorphism shines when you have collections of mixed types:
Animal[] animals = { new Dog(...), new Cat(...), new Bird(...) };
for (Animal a : animals) {
    a.makeSound(); // each calls its own version!
}
This allows you to write code that works with any Animal without knowing the specific type.

Abstract Classes
An abstract class cannot be instantiated — you cannot create objects from it. It serves as a template for subclasses. Abstract methods have no body — subclasses must implement them:
public abstract class Shape {
    public abstract double area(); // no body!
    public void describe() {
        System.out.println("Area: " + area());
    }
}
Any class with at least one abstract method must be declared abstract.

Interfaces
An interface is a completely abstract type defining a contract. It contains abstract methods (and constants). Classes implement interfaces with 'implements'. A class can implement multiple interfaces (unlike single inheritance).
public interface Drawable {
    void draw();
    void resize(double factor);
}
public class Circle extends Shape implements Drawable {
    public void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing circle"); }
    ...
}

The instanceof Operator
Use instanceof to check an object's type before casting:
if (animal instanceof Dog) {
    Dog d = (Dog) animal;
    d.fetch();
}

examples.code:
public abstract class Shape {
    protected String color;

    public Shape(String color) {
        this.color = color;
    }

    public abstract double area();

    public void describe() {
        System.out.printf("%s %s with area %.2f%n",
            color, getClass().getSimpleName(), area());
    }
}

public class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;
    public Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super(color);
        this.radius = radius;
    }
    @Override
    public double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; }
}

public class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double width, height;
    public Rectangle(String color, double width, double height) {
        super(color);
        this.width = width;
        this.height = height;
    }
    @Override
    public double area() { return width * height; }
}

public class Main {
